    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="section">
                <head>Letter 21: 6 June 1806<lb/></head>
                <list rendition="#nostyle">
                    <item><hi rend="bold">Physical form:</hi> One half sheet folded into 2 leaves
                        (12.7 x 20.3 cm); fol. 2<hi rend="sup">r</hi> blank; 2<hi
                            rend="sup">v</hi> is cover</item>
                    <item><hi rend="bold">Cover:</hi> Miss Rickards / Church Row / Hampstead /
                        Middlesex</item>
                    <item><hi rend="bold">PM:</hi> 7 o’Clock JU 6 180[6] N.T</item>
                    <item><hi rend="bold">WM:</hi> Part of a crest</item>
                    <item><hi rend="bold">SM:</hi> Misc MS 4362</item>
                </list>
            </div>
            <div type="letter">
                <opener>
                    <salute rendition="#indent1">My dear Miss Rickards,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p rend="noCount" rendition="#firstline">I am much obliged to M<hi rend="sup"
                        >rs</hi> Rickards &amp; yourself for your kind invitation, but it will not
                    be in our power to accept of it&#8212;As to Miss Estlin,<note place="foot"
                        resp="editors"> "Miss Estlin": See Note 1 to Letter 20.</note> she will be
                    returned to Bristol by the time you mention. &amp; we shall ourselves be just on
                    the eve of a journey, as M<hi rend="sup">r</hi> Barbauld has to preach the
                    annual Sermon of the South Unitarians at Lewes this year, &amp; I shall
                    accompany him if the weather is favourable, &amp; take a little tour.<note
                        place="foot" resp="editors"> RB preached the sermon at the annual meeting of
                        the Southern Unitarian Book Society, at Lewes in Sussex, on 25 June;
                        afterwards the Barbaulds visited the Isle of Wight (<title level="m"
                            >ALBVE</title>, 436).</note> We must therefore defer to some future time
                    the pleasure of visiting Hampstead again&#8212;Indeed I must come &amp; pick
                    up my goods &amp; chattels before we get into our new house,<note place="foot"
                        resp="editors"> "our new house": After renting in Stoke Newington the
                        Barbaulds bought a house in Church Road. They took occupancy in
                        September.</note> &amp; therefore you will be so good as to remember that we
                    shall claim our <hi rend="underline">chairs</hi>, probably in two or three
                    month’s time. I<lb/>

                    <hi rendition="#catchword">am</hi><lb/></p>

                <p rend="noCount">[<emph>fol 1<hi rend="sup">v</hi></emph>] am glad to hear so good
                    an account of worthy M<hi rend="sup">rs</hi> Plumptre.<note place="foot"
                        resp="editors"> "Mrs. Plumptre": See Note 3 to Letter 17.</note> Remember us
                    to Miss Baillies &amp; all our friends&#8212;If you see M<hi rend="sup">r</hi>
                        Lewis<note place="foot" resp="editors"> "Mr. Lewis": A Hampstead
                        neighbor.</note> tell him how sorry we were to be abroad when he called&#8212;I
                    have not just now time to write more, nor indeed any thing particular to say but
                    that which I hope you need not be told that I am Your’s &amp; M<hi rend="sup"
                        >rs</hi> Rickards </p>

                <closer>
                    <salute rendition="#indent6">aff<hi rend="sup">te</hi> &amp; faithful</salute>
                    <signed rendition="#indent7">AL Barbauld</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <p rend="noCount">Miss Estlin desires her Compts &amp; thanks for your invitation</p>
                </postscript>
                <dateline>Friday noon</dateline>
            </div>
        </body>
